This not only confirms that at least some dinosaurs had feathers, a theory already widespread, but also provides details that fossils usually cannot provide, such as color and three-dimensional arrangement.
Scientists say that the plumage of this animal was chestnut brown on top and pale or carotenoid in color underneath.
This discovery also allows a better understanding of the evolution of feathers in birds.
Given that dinosaur feathers do not have a fully developed shaft, known as a rachis, but nonetheless show other characteristics unique to feathers - barbs and barbules - researchers have deduced that the rachis was probably an evolutionary development subsequent to these other characteristics.
The structure of the feathers suggests that they were not used for flight but rather for temperature regulation or display. Researchers have suggested that, even though it is the tail of a young dinosaur, the sample shows adult plumage rather than the down of a chick.
Scientists specify that it is indeed the tail of a juvenile dinosaur, but the sample reveals plumage belonging to an adult individual, not a young one.
